[[File:Giuseppe Aprile - Placidi venti ameni - British Library Add MS 14193 f7101v.jpg|thumb|A page from the manuscript for ''Placide venti ameni'' by Giuseppe Aprile, written in his own hand.]] '''Giuseppe Aprile''' (28 October 1731 – 11 January 1813) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[castrato]] singer and music teacher. He was also known as 'Sciroletto' or 'Scirolino'.
Aprile was born in [[Martina Franca]]. After studying with [[Gregorio Sciroli]], composer and singing instructor, in [[Naples]], he began his singing career in 1752 at the [[Teatro San Carlo]] in Naples. He then began a great career, performing in prominent theatres throughout Italy, [[Germany]], and even Madrid. His voice could reach E5. He withdrew from the stage in 1785 and became a singing instructor in Naples. [[Domenico Cimarosa]], [[Michael Kelly (tenor)|Michael Kelly]] and [[Emma, Lady Hamilton]] were among his pupils. {{See LMST|Giuseppe|Aprile}} He wrote a popular book on singing instruction, ''The Italian Method of Singing, with 36 Solfeggi'' (1791).
